<h2>Environment-Specific Configuration</h2>

<p>Melodic does not enforce a specific strategy for managing environments, but the <code>loadConfig()</code> method supports multiple calls with deep merging, which gives you a clean pattern for layered configuration.</p>

<h3>Strategy: Base + Override Files</h3>

<p>Create a base config with shared settings and a per-environment override:</p>

<pre><code>config/
&boxv;&boxh;&boxh; config.json              &larr; Shared defaults
&boxv;&boxh;&boxh; config.development.json  &larr; Dev overrides
&boxur;&boxh;&boxh; config.production.json   &larr; Production overrides</code></pre>

<p>Then load both in your bootstrap, with the override file second:</p>

<pre><code>$env = getenv('APP_ENV') ?: 'development';

$app-&gt;loadConfig('config/config.json');
$app-&gt;loadConfig("config/config.{$env}.json");</code></pre>

<p>The second file only needs to contain the keys that differ. Everything else is inherited from the base config.</p>

<h3>Strategy: Environment Variables</h3>

<p>For sensitive values like database credentials and signing keys, use environment variables and set them in config after loading the file:</p>

<pre><code>$app-&gt;loadConfig('config/config.json');

// Override sensitive values from environment
$config = $app-&gt;config();
$config-&gt;set('database.dsn', getenv('DB_DSN') ?: $config-&gt;get('database.dsn'));
$config-&gt;set('database.username', getenv('DB_USER') ?: $config-&gt;get('database.username'));
$config-&gt;set('database.password', getenv('DB_PASS') ?: $config-&gt;get('database.password'));
$config-&gt;set('auth.local.signingKey', getenv('JWT_SECRET') ?: $config-&gt;get('auth.local.signingKey'));</code></pre>

<div class="callout callout-warning">
    <p><strong>Important:</strong> Never commit production secrets (database passwords, signing keys, client secrets) to version control. Use environment variables, a secrets manager, or a <code>config.production.json</code> file deployed separately from your codebase.</p>
</div>

<h3>Strategy: Programmatic Overrides</h3>

<p>You can also use the <code>Configuration::set()</code> method to override any value at runtime, regardless of what the JSON file contains:</p>

<pre><code>$app-&gt;loadConfig('config/config.json');

$config = $app-&gt;config();
$config-&gt;set('app.debug', false);
$config-&gt;set('cors.allowedOrigins', ['https://production.example.com']);</code></pre>

<div class="callout callout-tip">
    <p><strong>Tip:</strong> The <code>app</code> section (e.g., <code>app.name</code>, <code>app.debug</code>) is not consumed by the framework itself &mdash; it is a convention for your own application settings. You can add any keys you like and access them with <code>$app-&gt;config('my.custom.key')</code>.</p>
</div>
